    "messageBody": "<div id=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><html><head></head>Stefan,<div class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><br class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"></div><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">Thank you for the link. After a cursory glance, it seems like digging into Hamcrest to assert that an optional value is empty, for example, is more work for the user than it’s worth. I would rather stick to David’s suggestion of assertEquals(x, Optional.empty()) for this case, unless the assertion was especially complex. Then, as I mentioned to David, that isn’t nearly as clean (in my opinion) as an assertEmpty would be.</div><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><br class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"></div><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">Best,</div><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">Mark</div><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><br class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"></div><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><br class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><div><blockquote><span title=\"qreply\"> <blockquote type=\"cite\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">On Oct 5, 2015, at 12:18 AM, Stefan Bechtold <a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"mailto:stefan.bechtold@...\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">stefan.bechtold@...</a> [junit] &lt;<a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"mailto:junit@yahoogroups.com\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">junit@yahoogroups.com</a>&gt; wrote:</div><br class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490Apple-interchange-newline\"><div class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><div id=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490ygrp-mlmsg\" style=\"font-size:13px;font-family:Arial, helvetica, clean, sans-serif;font-style:normal;font-variant:normal;font-weight:normal;letter-spacing:normal;text-indent:0px;text-transform:none;white-space:normal;word-spacing:0px;background-color:rgb(255, 255, 255);\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><div id=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490ygrp-msg\" style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><div id=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490ygrp-text\" style=\"line-height:1.22em;font-family:Georgia;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;margin:0px 0px 1em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><br class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490webkit-block-placeholder\"></div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">Hi Mark</div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"></div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">Actually, I think this sounds more as an addition to a matcher framework like hamcrest rather than an addition to JUnit itself. What do you think?&nbsp;</div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"></div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">see also:&nbsp;<a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://github.com/hamcrest/JavaHamcrest/issues/82\" style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">https://github.com/hamcrest/JavaHamcrest/issues/82</a></div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"></div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">all the best</div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"></div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">Stefan</div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"></div></div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">Am 04.10.2015 um 19:55 schrieb Mark Silvis<span class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span><a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"mailto:masilvis22@...\" style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">masilvis22@...</a><span class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490Apple-converted-space\">&nbsp;</span>[junit] &lt;<a rel=\"nofollow\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"mailto:junit@yahoogroups.com\" style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">junit@yahoogroups.com</a>&gt;:<br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"></div><blockquote type=\"cite\" style=\"margin:0px 0px 0px 4px;line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><span style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">&nbsp;</span><div id=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490ygrp-text\" style=\"line-height:1.22em;font-family:Georgia;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><p style=\"line-height:1.22em;margin:0px 0px 1em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">I would like to contribute to JUnit, and I think I have a good idea for a feature. I’ve found that it would be nice to have assertions that explicitly supported Java 8’s Optional class. I’m thinking something along the lines of assertEmpty() and assertPresent(). Would such an addition be welcomed?<br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">Thanks,<br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\">Mark<br style=\"line-height:1.22em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"></p></div></div></blockquote><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;margin:0px 0px 1em;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"><br class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490webkit-block-placeholder\"></div></div><div style=\"line-height:1.22em;color:rgb(255, 255, 255);height:0px;\" class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"></div></div></div></div></blockquote></span></blockquote></div><br class=\"ygrps-yiv-2125520490\"></div></html></div>", 
